I found the standard X-axis tensioner plate on the Mendelmax 3 was a pain to adjust and it was too easy to compress the bearings so they wouldn't spin well.

This is a screw-adjustable X-axis tensioner for the Mendelmax 3. It separates the fixing to the X-bar and the belt idler bearings to different screws. It squeezes into the gap at the end of the X-axis bar between the Z carriage angle fixings and the cable chain holder. At the moment you have to remove the cable chain holder to access the adjustment screw - I may make a longer version to avoid this but at the moment it seems to work OK.
I added a smooth idler pulley for my X belt so this tensioner will accept that but the standard bearings would also suffice (with appropriate washers to guide the belt).

Required hardware:
M3x30 screw and M3 nut to connect the tension arm to the idler. A washer at the screw end may be good.
2x M5x8 screws and 2x M5 T-nuts to connect the idler assembly to the X-axis bar.
1x M5x16 screw (or however long you want the adjustment distance to be) and 1x M5 nut this is for the adjustment.
1x M5x25 screw and nut, 2x 605XX bearings (or idler pulley kit) for the belt idler.

EDIT 1 Nov 2016: In the pic it shows that I didn't have a M3x30 to use as the axle between the two parts. So I just used a M3x25 and it is captive held in by the x bar.

EDIT 4 Nov 2016: The problem with the original parts were that the cable chain holder needed to be removed to adjust the X belt tension. Pretty soon after I installed the parts I realised that if they were reversed/mirrored then they could be installed upside-down and the cable chain holder would not need to be removed to make adjustments. facepalm
I have now had some time to mirror the parts and install and test that - yes - it works better now. I have updated the parts and the pictures with the mirrored versions.

comments.text: The M5x8 behind the tension arm that screws into the X-bar needs to be a flat head version so that the tension arm can rotate without hitting it.

I used a hot glue gun to fix the components into the case and CAT5 Ethernet wires the connect the pins. To save space I removed all metal pins from the boards like the OLED display or the clock module.

Edit: software is updated to v0.35: new feature: auto on-off: currently active, the screen turns on at every workday at 8:30 at turns off at 18:00

Edit: software is updated to v0.3: capable to show temperature, humidity, time and battery voltage.
As this is a battery powered project I really care about the power consumption. Basically the only thing that consumes power is the OLED (if it's powered on). The Arduino and the clock module is in sleep for the most of the time. If the screen is switched off the power consumption is ~11mA even though the software keeps all the functionality running like temperature logging or alarms.

description.text:
NOTE:
*new Version 3.1
-Improved locking between vertical and horizontal unit
-Improved bow-scope connector to right angle profile

*new Version 3.1.1
-Improved trailer stability and M3 pocket for "federndes Druckstueck"
-Added left hand (LH) support for vertical unit and dovetail horizontal counterpart

*new Version 3.1.2
-Added a shorter trailer version which is 30mm shorter, This should be enough to cover all distances. At the longer version, the scope would run into the arrow at the lower side.

*new Version 3.1.3: Long term experience changes:
-Lock screw cracked the horizontal dovetail when screw was locked to hard due to 45° front angle. This is now fixed
-Trailer connector craced when M3 screws where locked to hard. This is now strengthend.
###################################################################

This is a high precision recurve bow sight with following features:

-146mm netto vertical travel (116mm for the short version)
-fast movable by button
-Dual click
-precision verical ca. 0.08mm
-precision horizontal ca 0.07mm
-changable scope inlays
-10mm scope tunnel
-Riser connector with standard imperial thread.
-Detachable horizontal axis by dovetail connection, secured by locking screw for better transportation
-Lowered area on the right side of the trailer for a dial
-Made for right hand archers, but can be turned araound easily. Use LH version of vertical unit and dovetail so that locking screw stays on top for LH archers. (mainly a cosmetic problem)

I set a high value on getting both axis working without any clearance. For this, I tested a lot of clearances and came to 0.2mm for all pockets that touch metal parts.
Let me know if you have trouble with it.

What you need in addition:

Vertical:

2x 6mm aluminium smooth rods, Length 164mm (134mm for short version)
1x M5 Threaded rod length:
-186mm for one vertical control knob or 196mm for two on both ends
-156mm for one vertical control knob or 166mm for two on both ends

4x M2,5x12mm screws
4x M2,5 nuts
2x M3x14mm screw
3x M3 Stop nut
2x M3x10mm
2x Bearing 5mmx11mmx4mm
1x "federndes Druckstueck" e.g. http://www.maedler.de/Article/65460300
1x M5 Stopnut
3x M5 Nut
1x M5 Nut brass (Messing)
1x 0.8mm Federstahldraht ( spring steel wire) 300mm
1x M3x16mm

Horizontal:

2x M2,5x20mm
2x M2,5x12mm
4x M2,5 Nut
4x M4 Nut
1x M4 Stop Nut
1x "federndes Druckstueck" e.g. http://www.maedler.de/Article/65460300
2x 3mm smooth rods (i take here titanium alloy) Length 25mm

Connectors:
2x M3x18mm plus stop nuts
1x M5x25mm Din 931
1x M5 stop nut
1x Aluminium right angle, equal sided 15x15x3mm, length 250mm
2x 10-24 UNC 1 1/4 Zoll Length 31,75 mm Linsenkopfschraube

-5min Epoxy
-Silicon grease

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3 Steel Toolson Edition

Rafts:

No

No

0.2mm / 0.4mm

80%

Notes:

0.2mm for all small parts
0.4mm for trailer and connectors

Material: Green-Tec from Extrudr, because it is heat resistant up to 110C and is easy to rework (drilling etc.)

No part at all needs support structures, some parts have build in support that can be drilled out or removed

Objects need to be rotated in correct position for printing!

Print orientations:
-Trailer:
Lay down so that dial pocket is on the top
-Vertical and dovetail:
needs to be printed upwards, so that the dovetail profile is visible from the top
-All other parts should be easy to find out...

What tools do you need

-Screwdriver, Sand paper, rasp,
-M3 thread cutter to cut a thread for the M3 Federnde Druckstuecke
-5min. Epoxy or other glue

drilling bits:
-1mm to rework the indicator pocket (use the 0.8mm steel wire)
-1,5mm (to expand the hole on the dovetail that matches with the "Druckstück" Ball)
-2,5mm (to expand the M2,5mm drillings at the trailer and at the horizontal unit)
-3mm (to expand the horizontal rod pockets and the vertical lock block bolt pocket and all M3 holes)
-4mm for M4 rod holes
-5mm for M5 rod holes and lock screw pocket at horizontal unit
-6mm for 6mm alu rod holes at the vertical unit

Assembly Infos

The 6mm alu rods needs to be drilled with 2,5mm drilling bit at each end. Note: These holes need to be exactly parallel and centered on the radius, otherwise the M2,5 screws will not find their nut on the other side of the trailer.

Put the M3 stop nuts for the bow connector in their pockets BEFORE inserting and locking the back 6mm alu rod! The nuts will not be removable when the rod is in place.

Cut the M3 thread for the "federndes Druckstueck" before assembling the rods. All threads must be orthogonal, otherwise the ball will not be centered in the nocks on the knobs!

Use one "federndes Druckstueck" to create a nock at the top or bottom of the trailer. Adjust it so that it nocks into the vertical knob with a M5 Washer between them,

The dovetail must be sanded until fitting together.

The vertical quick adjust button needs to be sanded until it fits in the vertical housing. NOTE: start sand at the sides! There must not be any clearance in the vertical axis!
The M5 brass nut needs to be cut in 2 pieces, which are glued in the button with 5 min. epoxy.

Use steel wire and create a spring of ca. 15mm length. Put it between button and housing.
Use some mm of the steel wire and create the indicator needle. Glue it in the pocket of the vertical housing with 5min epoxy.

Use one "federndes Druckstueck" to create a nock at the right side of the horizontal axis.

NOTE:
cut the threads for the "federndes Druckstueck" not completely through the complete pocket! leave a half mm uncut at the ball end of the piece to create a natural friction to hold the screw in place without any glue...

Use 1mm -1.2mm washer between rightside and horizontal control knob so that there is no clearance at all in the horizontal axis.

Use silicon grease to make rods, dovetail and butoon smooth in movement...

title: WARBOTRON/MACHINE BOY VORTEX to IDW ROTORSTORM kit

description.text:
This kit is designed to convert Your Warbotron/Machine Boy Vortex to a IDW styled Rotorstorm.

I have changed transformation schematics (waist rotated 180 degrees to allow for an up-sweep of tail) plus some fiddling with arms. take a look a the pictures and You'll figure it out.

Thanks to my good friend Marcin Starzomski here

https://www.facebook.com/Printformers/?fref=ts

we have a great Rotorstorm head!
it has been slightly redesigned to fit inside during transformation, You just need to rotate it 180 degrees to face his back before transforming.

The tail transforms without detaching into the configuration shown in the pictures, the fins rotate 360 so the proper configuration can be reached without partsforming.

please be careful when installing the shoulder axle, I had mine printed slightly too tight and it snapped leaving half of it inside the socket. I STRONGLY SUGGEST TO PRINT THE AXLE IN HORIZONTAL POSITION, this way it will be much less prone to snapping in the worse possible way (when you print it vertically the circular layers will just snap off and will stay inside the body forcing you to drill them out, it's a pain, believe me)

the nose section will fit inside the back of the figure (under the flap), the hole in front is intended to house the original L-shaped connector (you need to remove it from the original nose/gun section). the long connecting rod that goes through it (and connects the front section that follow the nose) can be stored inside the body of the figure, underneath the nose section.

in order to remove the old canopy You need to knock the pin out with a small screwdriver and a hammer, then fit the canopy and squeeze the pin in with pliers.

the arm connectors go into holes in the arms and are used to store the split nose section in bot mode, and the wings in heli mode.

the smallest cylinder is intended to be installed on the bottom of the...butt, in one of the screw holes. it will prevent the helicopter from tipping back constantly. i ran out of energy before getting to landing gear, sorry :D

You have feet that nicely replace the originals. you need to play with them when transforming to get them out of the way of the tail. Warning - please mind the original balljoint pegs of the feet - if you print the feet in a way that the sockets are too tight You are very likely to brake the pegs, just as did I.

the knee cover fronts are to be detached and swapped during transformation, this way they will cover the back of the guns in alt mode and will also nicely continue the side line of the chopper.

you have to detach the back caps of the guns for transformation. there is no good place to store them - You can mount them on top in the gun holes in the flap, or underneath the wings in his hands.

all the files have been printed a couple of times now and are good to go, depending on your printers resolution and calibrations you will have to put some time in making the holes round and the tolerances sit, otherwise the prints will crack and get stress marks.

any questions please ask. i can write an assembly manual if required.

Ps - you need two shoulder connectors 01, two shoulder axles (please be very careful with those!), two rotor blades (obviously;), two feet, two arm connectors and two gun sets.

Enjoy!

description.text:
These are all the components for making a Shark Boy Costume.  It includes the Chest Harness, Weight Belt, Holsters (for the Sword) and a Shark Fin Sword.  
I'm debating on adding the Arm Gauntlets.  If there's enough interest in the Costume, I might get motivated and add them to the Set.

The Chest Plate, Holder and Shark Fin can be joined to make a Vest.  
I had issues printing the Chest Plate and created a recess for breaking up the back surface into smaller areas.  We also bent the Chest plate with a heat gun so that it wrapped to my son's Chest.  
The Sword is printed in two pieces and glued.  Sure, I could have created some kind of mechanical connector, but this was a last minute design.  I also dislike support material, which is why it's two pieces.  
The sword has a hook on the end and when fed through the bottom of the Sword Holder, it will stay in place.  A quick twist with a downward pull and the sword will come out.  As a side note, the sword stayed in the Holder all night during Halloween.  
The Shark Fin does come to a Point and after sanding, I added yellow tape and wrapped it around it for safety.  I poured this Monster Glue inside the Fin that expands and dries white.  It strengthened the shark fin and protected it from snapping at the end.  
The Sword Holder snaps into the Belt Weights.  It should stay in place, but after I threaded a belt through the weights - I added a screw for holding it in place.  A 1 Inch belt should work - we had an old leather one that worked perfect.  
The Shark Fin fits into the Holder with the 4 Tabs.  I later glued these in place.  
For those FEA savvy - there's a weak spot on the guide rails of the Sword blade.  It held up, but for durability I would add something to strengthen the smallest point of the rails from breaking under fun, I mean stress.

description.text:
The rekenrek is a abacus-like math learning tool that both my kids have used in their early math education. This version was designed to be easily assembled with a #2 pencil. The racks can be attached to each other with small nibs. Typically, a rekenrek has two rows with ten beads (2 color groups of 5) that are fixed. But with this design, kids can add and remove the beads, depending on the exercise and complexity level. The beads range from 1-10 sides, representing different numbers. You can position multiple racks horizontally or vertically, and incorporate any number of beads for a fun range of exercises around number concepts, addition, subtraction, as well as multiplication. Since #2 pencils might be scarce in many classrooms, there's a small hole at either end (with grooves on the bottom and sides) for a string. Note: the pieces are uploaded individually as it gives the most flexibility for grouping prints. The pieces are listed with their numbers as "w" for with number and "wo" for without number. Figured I'd just give folks the choice. More info on my blog.

An experiment in printing hollow arms and a monocoque chassis for a very light weight, indoor brushed quadcopter. I was aiming for the strength/crashability of my lightweight Gnat design, but with improved stiffness and handling.

title: Roller Bearing Spool Holder for 6.5"D x 3.5" W spools for Replicator 2

description.text:
This is a roller brearing spool holder for the Makerbot 2 for smaller wider rolls of filament (MatterHackers.com).  This is based on my previous spool holder but has some improvements, the biggest being support isn't needed to print the 'top hat' shape.  
This holder is held together by gravity.  When you remove a spool, make sure you push on the holder to keep the bearings in place or you'll have parts all over the place.   Some day I'll add something to hold it together so that doesn't happen, or someone else can add that.  Once you get used to it, you don't even think about it when removeing a spool.  
I've included 2 different shafts, one for each side of the machine.  I keep my Makerbot sized spool holder on the right, and this one on the left.

1) Print 9 bearings, no support, minimal fill.  
2) Print the spool holder (top hat).  I used med resolution, about 10% fill.  
3) Print the shaft in fine resolution and about 15% fill for strength.  This part needs support.  
4) Assemble the parts.
